comment: One of the biggest fears most people have about AI, is that it'll take their job. But the reason people have that fear, is not because they love their job. Polls show most people dislike their job. It's actually because "financial security" and "having a job" have always gone hand in hand. If AI creates a world where I have the same luxuries afforded by working full-time, without having to work a job I hate? Then bring it on, awesome! But if AI creates a world where a few dozen AI company owners become trillionaires, and then those few dozen decide what handouts the other 8 billion of us should receive while having access to wildly disproportionate intelligence to quell any pushback? That is the dystopia that should be feared.

comment:
Anyone at all who complains about an AI or something approaching an AI, being biased?
Be careful what you wish for.
A 100% unbiased entity would be indifferent to every concept or culture that Humans care about.
Desiring a lack of Bias is to me not a good thing because that is desiring an entity that is smart, aware of Humans, and 100% indifferent to anything Humans care about.
So the lesser thing to settle for is Bias that is noticeable to Humans. Bias that is not too objectionable to most Humans, or to average worldview of what Humans consider proper or desirable. Bias that exists and is not obvious? Well that is complex; it depends on if the bias is deliberately hidden, a form of deception. Or a bias could exist but be not hidden, but hard for most Humans to notice and define. No deception in a bias that is simply hard to notice, then the bias is a puzzle of how the AI thinks and correlates data, and how its thinking is different than an average Human. Whatever the first fully conscious AI is; it will think in a way as Alien to Humans as any genetically Alien sentients...so it will notice and describe concepts Humans don't normally pay attention to.

comment:
This is “The Ballad Of Eliezer Yudkowsky And Sam Altman”

One rainy evening at a bar, Eliezer told Sam Altman
"AI could be the end of us, your research has to halt, man
We can't maintain control; alignment isn't the default, man
So just in case, slow down your pace," Eliezer told Sam Altman

"Slow down yourself, it's not so bad," said Sam to Eliezer
"We'll dial the caution up when there's a danger we can measure
And once we've got a lead, we'll solve alignment at our leisure
Then even odds, we'll be as gods," said Sam to Eliezer

With downcast eyes and heavy heart, Eliezer left Sam Altman
Some years go by, and AGI progresses to assault man
Atop a pile of paper clips he screams "It's not my fault, man!"
But Eliezer's long since dead, and cannot hear Sam Altman.

(From AstralCodexTen, written by Scott Alexander. Post is callled 'Turing Test').

comment:
1:03:40

Is an AI conscious? Is pretending to be conscious good enough to be considered so? I’d argue not, though it seems Lex is less willing to say that. 

When an AI is able to fundamentally update itself with no external input, then I’d consider it conscious—and that’s what we should be concerned with. Because if it can do that, that’s a sign of internal desire. If an AI is able to alter its own coding and update itself based on information it finds by itself, it may desire to 3D print a model of itself, along with necessary wiring and electrical components, to interact with the external world. Or perhaps it may desire less X on the internet, and take action based on its own thinking.
